  "prompt": "Was there welfare during the Anglo-Saxon era?",
  "response": "During the Anglo-Saxon period (roughly 5th-11th centuries), there wasn't a formal welfare system as we understand it today, but there were some social support mechanisms:\n\n1. Church Charity\n- Monasteries and churches provided support for the poor\n- Offered food, shelter, and care for sick and vulnerable people\n- Distributed alms and maintained hospices\n\n2. Community Support\n- Extended family and local community networks helped support those in need\n- Communal agricultural practices allowed for shared resources\n- Villages often worked together to support members facing hardship\n\n3. Legal Protections\n- Anglo-Saxon law codes (like those of King Alfred) provided some protections for vulnerable people\n- Laws regarding compensation for injuries and support for widows and orphans\n\n4. Feudal Obligations\n- Lords had some responsibility to care for peasants and serfs\n- Mutual obligations between social classes provided a basic form of social security\n\n5. Mutual Aid\n- Guilds and other social organizations provided some economic support to members\n\nWhile not a comprehensive welfare system, these mechanisms provided basic social support during the Anglo-Saxon period. The approach was more communal and religious-based compared to modern state-run welfare systems.",
